    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-11-29T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-11-29T16:00:00-05:00" n="817"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d817">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.48 Refugees/999: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-11-29T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 29, 1938—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>214. Your 664, November 28, 5 p.m. Rublee reported on November 25<note n="70"
                        xml:id="d817fn70">Telegram No. 1354, not printed.</note> that he had been
                    advised by an “unofficial” British source, presumably the one mentioned in your
                    647, that arrangements were being made, with Hitler’s consent, for Schacht to
                    visit London within 2 weeks to confer with Rublee. Rublee was last night advised
                    by the Foreign Office that Ogilvie-Forbes<note n="71" xml:id="d817fn71">Sir
                        George Ogilvie-Forbes, British Chargé in Germany.</note> had been officially
                    assured by the Reich Government that a high ranking emissary would proceed to
                    London to confer with him in the immediate future.</p>
                <p>Please check at once with the British Chargé.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
